## Tips and Tricks

* **Must load packages** at the beginning of the document/before you try to do anything with them.



* **If you're curious** about a line of code, package, dataset etc., simply type ? followed by the "title" of the thing you're wondering about.




* **Message=FALSE** takes away the long, unnecessary message that comes with packages like tidyverse.

```{r, message= FALSE}
library(tidyverse)
?tidyverse

```





* **`relocate()`** moves variables around and by default, moves them to the front. 

```{r}
library(nycflights13)
flights |>
  relocate(air_time,)
```





* **`rename()`** keeps all existing variables and just renames those that you tell it to.

```{r}
flights |>
  rename(tail_num=tailnum)
```





* **`select()`** renames variables, inside of the parenthesis use `=` and put the new name on the LHS and the old name on the RHS. But select gets rid of the other columns not being called upon. 

```{r}
flights |>
  select(tail_num=tailnum)
```



* **scripts** don't have any text formatting, only code and code comments. They're useful for runing code on a server or computing cluster.


* **comments** are ignored by r and only for humans reading the code. Goes from wherever the # starts until the end of that line. 


* **`mean(dataset)`** gives you the mean of a data set. There are also functions like this for `median()`, and `


* **to make a ggplot,** use the following example. outline:

```{r}
library(nycflights13)


ggplot(data=flights, mapping=aes(x=dep_time, y=arr_time)) +
  geom_point()
```



